{% raw %}<h2>The Problem</h2>

<p>React can wrap components without adding DOM elements &mdash; <code>&lt;&gt;...&lt;/&gt;</code> (Fragments), <code>Context.Provider</code>, render props, and higher-order components all compose behavior without injecting wrapper nodes. In a custom-elements framework like Web Everything, every custom element is a real DOM node. This creates problems:</p>

<ul>
  <li><strong>CSS layout pollution</strong> &mdash; A wrapper <code>&lt;my-provider&gt;</code> between a Flex/Grid parent and its children breaks the parent&ndash;child layout relationship</li>
  <li><strong>Semantic noise</strong> &mdash; Extra elements in the DOM that carry no semantic meaning</li>
  <li><strong>Accessibility tree bloat</strong> &mdash; Screen readers may enumerate elements that add no value</li>
  <li><strong>Selector complexity</strong> &mdash; CSS selectors must account for intermediate wrappers (<code>.parent > my-provider > .child</code>)</li>
</ul>

<p>This research catalogs every pattern and runtime solution available, evaluates what Web Everything already implements, and identifies the remaining gaps.</p>


<h2>What Frameworks Do</h2>

<table>
  <thead>
    <tr>
      <th>Framework</th>
      <th>DOM-Less Patterns</th>
      <th>Mechanism</th>
    </tr>
  </thead>
  <tbody>
    <tr>
      <td><strong>React</strong></td>
      <td>Fragment, Context.Provider, render props, HOCs, Portals, cloneElement</td>
      <td>Virtual DOM &mdash; components are functions, not DOM nodes</td>
    </tr>
    <tr>
      <td><strong>Vue</strong></td>
      <td><code>&lt;template&gt;</code> wrapper, <code>&lt;Teleport&gt;</code>, <code>&lt;Transition&gt;</code>, <code>&lt;Suspense&gt;</code></td>
      <td>Compiler removes <code>&lt;template&gt;</code>; virtual components use comment placeholders</td>
    </tr>
    <tr>
      <td><strong>Angular</strong></td>
      <td><code>&lt;ng-container&gt;</code>, <code>&lt;ng-template&gt;</code>, structural directives (<code>*ngIf</code>, <code>*ngFor</code>)</td>
      <td>Compiler replaces with comment markers at build time</td>
    </tr>
    <tr>
      <td><strong>Svelte</strong></td>
      <td><code>{#if}</code>, <code>{#each}</code>, <code>{#await}</code>, <code>&lt;svelte:element&gt;</code></td>
      <td>Compiler generates imperative DOM code &mdash; blocks become comment-delimited regions</td>
    </tr>
    <tr>
      <td><strong>Solid</strong></td>
      <td><code>&lt;Show&gt;</code>, <code>&lt;For&gt;</code>, <code>&lt;Switch&gt;/&lt;Match&gt;</code>, <code>&lt;Portal&gt;</code></td>
      <td>Components use comment nodes as anchors; zero wrapper elements</td>
    </tr>
    <tr>
      <td><strong>Lit</strong></td>
      <td><code>nothing</code> sentinel, <code>repeat</code>/<code>when</code>/<code>choose</code>/<code>cache</code> directives</td>
      <td>Comment-based template part system for tracking dynamic regions</td>
    </tr>
    <tr>
      <td><strong>Stencil</strong></td>
      <td><code>&lt;Host&gt;</code>, Fragment, functional components</td>
      <td>Functional components inlined during virtual DOM rendering</td>
    </tr>
  </tbody>
</table>

<p><strong>Key insight:</strong> Every framework solves this either through <em>compile-time erasure</em> (removing grouping elements at build time) or <em>comment-based markers</em> (invisible DOM nodes that delimit regions). Web Everything already uses both patterns.</p>


